Notebook[{
Cell[TextData[{
 ButtonBox["In the comments to my article",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://habr.com/ru/articles/772984/comments/#comment_26162754"], 
    None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://habr.com/ru/articles/772984/comments/#comment_26162754"],
 ", user ",
 ButtonBox["@Refridgerator",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://habr.com/ru/users/refridgerator/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://habr.com/ru/users/refridgerator/"],
 " wrote in response to my question that the Wolfram Language (WL) is missing \
the following:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9127694608984365`*^9, 
  3.912769494698516*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"77cae933-6afc-43e1-a58d-\
e446e51adf85"],

Cell["\<\
OOP, operator overloading, strict typing, event-driven programming, \
data-driven programming, parallel programming with synchronization \
primitives, debugging tools, execution speed. (c) @Refridgerator\
\>", "Abstract",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.912769562391145*^9, 
  3.912769571207039*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d6878523-2eae-4114-b8b4-\
b361c75dd0be"],

Cell["\<\
I\[CloseCurlyQuote]m well aware that there are some historical stereotypes \
around Mathematica. They usually present WL as a calculator on steroids, or \
just a toy, or more of a query language that can be used to additionally \
solve equations and graphs. Today I will try to show that there is more to \
the language than just graphs, equations and integrals. I hardly have enough \
energy to write in detail about every item on the list, but I will try to \
explain at least some of them.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912769649674076*^9},ExpressionUUID->"74fbb1b3-0269-48d3-8bbf-\
34e1787db4fb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 ButtonBox["I'm not the first to tackle this challenge",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://mathematica.stackexchange.com/questions/119991/which-object-\
oriented-paradigm-approach-to-use-in-mathematica"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://mathematica.stackexchange.com/questions/119991/which-object-\
oriented-paradigm-approach-to-use-in-mathematica"],
 ". There are already functions on Mathematica Stack Exchange and elsewhere \
that do something similar. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912922790974311*^9, {3.9129228853141584`*^9, 
   3.9129228853298044`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e2a8e00e-a529-4e23-a7be-\
0f4b781097de"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["TLDR", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.912769662560832*^9, 
  3.912769663578675*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1ae4883d-31d9-4607-b774-\
9ecf7a205388"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "There\[CloseCurlyQuote]s a lot of text in the article, if you don\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]t want to get bogged down and just want to get a feel for \
what I\[CloseCurlyQuote]m going to write about below - there are shorter and \
simpler instructions in the Objects package repository and on the page in the \
",
 ButtonBox["Paclet Repository",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://resources.wolframcloud.com/PacletRepository/resources/\
KirillBelov/Objects/"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://resources.wolframcloud.com/PacletRepository/resources/KirillBelov/\
Objects/"],
 "."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912769672988183*^9, {3.9127697146868067`*^9, 
   3.912769714687795*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a078c111-3dcf-46a5-8ca1-\
3f7ce4ce78f9"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Mutable objects", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9127697209439063`*^9, 
  3.912769728011672*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"52c8fa2a-ea2b-46e8-bd33-\
8d62f9b23da8"],

Cell["\<\
As we all know, WL follows the principle of immutable objects. The only way \
to change an expression (rather than create a whole new one) is to use the \
Part function and replace part of the expression, which is stored in the \
symbol\[CloseCurlyQuote]s own values. To put it in human terms, we can simply \
create a variable that stores a complex object and change that object. This \
is quite a strong difference between WL and languages like Java, C#, Python \
and JavaScript, which imposes its own limitations, but has its advantages. I \
like the concept in principle, but I\[CloseCurlyQuote]ve always wanted to be \
able to write code something similar to what you can write in Python. \
Modifiable objects were added to the language not too long ago, but they are \
so inconvenient that I use them very little (and I made my own objects \
earlier). Modifying bare symbols directly is also inconvenient. So, as a \
result, I had an idea to implement my own objects - I will show them now and \
then tell you how they work.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9127697407197757`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"eef5dd56-d2b1-4e06-82a7-\
7f29b215c4a2"],

Cell["\<\
First, you need to have one of the latest versions of WL. Then you need to \
install a package from Paclet Repository, which is called rather \
unpretentious - Objects:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9127697578174047`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"f5231b2a-0ab9-42be-b62e-\
ce3f4b5c108c"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

