Cell["\<\
By default, all object properties are set to Automatic unless a value has \
been set for them when defining the type itself.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129211316846004`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"a16326b0-8682-4579-a8a1-\
f4b2b280d1eb"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Encapsulation", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.91292114428158*^9},ExpressionUUID->"012456fc-81e8-483b-ad1c-5f352d4b71a1"],

Cell["\<\
One of the principles that allows you to implement OOP. I should mention here \
that I did not strictly follow all the principles. First of all, I looked at \
how something works in other languages such as Python, Java, C# and \
JavaScript and transferred it to modifiable objects in the way that I \
personally found most convenient for WL. That\[CloseCurlyQuote]s why there \
won\[CloseCurlyQuote]t be a classical encapsulation like in Java and C#, but \
an incomplete encapsulation without hiding, i.e. like in Python. After all, \
all objects are actually expressions, and we can access any part of any \
expression without any problems. So objects contain properties, but they \
cannot be made private. On the other hand a language like Python is not \
hindered by this. Hiding may not work, but the main purpose of encapsulation \
is fulfilled - now all the properties of an object are enclosed inside it and \
their values can only be accessed directly through the object. Thus we can \
build complex objects, and at higher levels build their interaction without \
thinking about how they are realized inside. How to work with properties?\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129211586103306`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"3814669c-0b91-4b56-a8d2-\
862c3613490c"],

Cell["This is how a property can be extracted:", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129211718399982`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"516e91b8-4a9e-42ce-847b-\
1bd227800bf6"],

