Cell["\<\
We have dealt with property inheritance. Of course, there are still some \
subtleties, but let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s move on to more important issues. What \
about methods? Where are they? We haven\[CloseCurlyQuote]t heard a word about \
them yet! Now we\[CloseCurlyQuote]re getting to them. First, a little bit of \
lengthy reasoning.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912921989765603*^9},ExpressionUUID->"0b935fc8-b0ad-408d-b79b-\
2bfecf7685a7"],

Cell["\<\
There are several ways to create and save a definition in the Wolfram \
Language. The method depends first on where the definition is saved, and \
second on the symbol to which the definition is associated. When we create a \
standard function like this:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912921997841236*^9},ExpressionUUID->"ef360a9f-8db8-4800-aee9-\
22600f91b2ff"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"func1", "[", 
   RowBox[{"x_", ",", "y_"}], "]"}], ":=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"x", "^", "2"}], "+", 
   RowBox[{"y", "^", "3"}], "-", "1"}]}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9129220035047092`*^9, 3.9129220035047092`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[35]:=",ExpressionUUID->"e2b681a9-3f25-4552-b447-5fe3c102a15f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "That function definition is associated with the name ",
 StyleBox["func1",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". It will now be stored in ",
 StyleBox["DownValues",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " for this symbol:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912922017524804*^9},ExpressionUUID->"31c4c15b-be3f-40f1-961e-\
330a84e02131"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"DownValues", "[", "func1", "]"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9129220317075853`*^9, 3.912922031723214*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[36]:=",ExpressionUUID->"c2144334-cb43-408d-969d-8bd0fe941134"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"HoldPattern", "[", 
    RowBox[{"func1", "[", 
     RowBox[{"x_", ",", "y_"}], "]"}], "]"}], "\[RuleDelayed]", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["x", "2"], "+", 
    SuperscriptBox["y", "3"], "-", "1"}]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.9129220321006126`*^9},
 CellLabel->"Out[36]=",ExpressionUUID->"46415525-92db-4838-9fdf-5d340d3bd906"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["\<\
And naturally we can create a function that is defined on our object and \
changes it in some way. Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s say we want the person we \
created to be able to say something, for example, the word \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]hello\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] and say his name. This \
is the kind of function we can create for that:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129220443826275`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"1f806190-15bb-42ad-89bf-\
32476573d4de"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"sayHi", "[", "human_Human", "]"}], ":=", 
   RowBox[{"Echo", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"StringTemplate", "[", "\"\<Hi! My name is `1`\>\"", "]"}], "[", 
      RowBox[{"human", "[", "\"\<Name\>\"", "]"}], "]"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"Row", "[", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"human", "[", "\"\<Name\>\"", "]"}], ",", "\"\< says: \>\""}],
        "}"}], "]"}]}], "]"}]}], "\n"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"sayHi", "[", "Kirill", "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9129220507630424`*^9, 3.9129220507630424`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[37]:=",ExpressionUUID->"cc6cfd24-37bb-4d36-8a04-8f0050fbc513"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  TagBox[
   TemplateBox[{"\"Kirill Belov\"", "\" says: \""},
    "RowDefault"],
   "EchoLabel"], "  ", "\<\"Hi! My name is Kirill Belov\"\>"}]], "Echo",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912922051376356*^9},ExpressionUUID->"9d4d2a00-1b35-4918-bca0-\
fe2c7bac08f5"],

Cell[BoxData["\<\"Hi! My name is Kirill Belov\"\>"], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.9129220513924437`*^9},
 CellLabel->"Out[38]=",ExpressionUUID->"110ae8fc-7338-4635-a303-c72d4289e5fd"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note that I have specified the ",
 StyleBox["human_Human",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " template with the expression header after the underscore. This allows you \
to specify the exact type on which the function will work. With any other \
type it simply won\[CloseCurlyQuote]t work and will return all Input back. \
Thus, we can use strong typing in function arguments, i.e. typing where there \
is no implicit type conversion. This means that our function will work on the \
",
 StyleBox["Human",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " type and only on it. What about inheritance? Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s create \
a derived type, for example student, and try to call the same function on it:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129220626127768`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"7df84dfa-12cf-4b63-8f1d-\
ffdd6ef1813d"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"CreateType", "[", 
   RowBox[{"Student", ",", "Human", ",", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"\"\<Course\>\"", "->", "1"}], "}"}]}], "]"}], 
  "\n"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Ivan", "=", 
   RowBox[{"Student", "[", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<Name\>\"", "->", "\"\<Ivan\>\""}], "]"}]}], 
  "\n"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"sayHi", "[", "Ivan", "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.912922096738535*^9, 3.912922096738535*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[39]:=",ExpressionUUID->"149a9fc0-7f2d-4c6d-848b-3ca9591b29a3"],

