Cell["\<\
In this way we can easily build a hierarchy of types, where instances will \
only store their own data, and definitions will be bound to the symbol \
corresponding to the type, but most importantly both properties and methods \
are inherited when creating descendants.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912922272131542*^9},ExpressionUUID->"975e87d5-cb2f-451b-b131-\
a115600f2d7a"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Polymorphism", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912922283264017*^9},ExpressionUUID->"4de966d0-65a4-4ab9-9cd8-\
252cb98b5a6d"],

Cell["\<\
Polymorphism in WL is different from how it is implemented in the other \
languages I\[CloseCurlyQuote]ve already listed many times. First of all, if \
we take Python, Java, C# and JavaScript again, none of these languages have \
strong typing. Python and JS have none at all, and Java and C# have weak \
typing. At the same time, the first pair has dynamic typing and the second \
pair has static typing. WL has strong dynamic typing where possible.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129222928682036`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"9f17c17d-d086-4413-80f6-\
c70e606f19ee"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "I would like to point out once again that the classification of programming \
languages and the discussion of paradigms and approach is a very holivorous \
topic and I like to discuss it and would be glad if someone in the comments \
shares his/her opinion. So, to give additional food for holivar, I should \
clarify that strong and weak typing in the context of the article means the \
relation of function and arguments (because there is nothing else in WL), and \
dynamic and static typing refers to the way of allocating memory for objects. \
In Java and C# this can be done only once for a specific type and even ",
 StyleBox["var",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["dynamic",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " will not help to overwrite an already stored value with a value of a \
different type. JS and Python, on the contrary, allow you to write anything \
to any variable. It turns out that in WL you can dynamically change the type \
of a variable at any moment, but at the same time functions always check the \
type of arguments and do not do implicit conversion."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.912922302658474*^9},ExpressionUUID->"dade4001-27d6-4459-b4e3-\
72019ee0b99b"],

Cell["\<\
Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s move on to the peculiarities of polymorphism. In the \
previous sections I said that some of the functionality of my package is \
similar to JS, and some of it is similar to Python and a little bit to C#. We \
know that C# and Java easily support method overloading, while Python as far \
as I understand does it through crutches with attributes, eventually creating \
a definition with conditions. In JS there is no overloading at all - you need \
to manually check arguments in conditional operators. If I am wrong - I \
sincerely hope to be corrected.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129223137620597`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"77af6a32-c703-4116-a2d8-\
60d66187345a"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Overload", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129223403150225`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"84b11c57-5228-4472-b14a-\
5d5acd87e13d"],

Cell["\<\
But how does overloading work in WL? (I should clarify that this is not a \
feature of my package specifically, and the language knows how to do it all \
by default). Function overloading is most similar to Java and C#. But there \
is one important difference. Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s say I can create a class \
and two methods with the same name but different parameters:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129223502823954`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"d8ee92b9-d61c-42a2-82c7-\
4104fed63982"],

