Cell["\<\
Note that the definition for \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]first\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] is preserved and inherited from Human! Even though \
the signatures are the same and we have created a definition for one overload \
and no definition for the other. Everything will work the same with \
conditions, checks, and alternatives!\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129225412923393`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"632506cb-a5b8-4ec9-9860-\
f33a8b831481"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Real examples", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9129225505981154`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"ae8d5111-2348-4171-8924-\
4179ca369f90"],

Cell["\<\
This article is already quite long. And I\[CloseCurlyQuote]m afraid it will \
be hard to read. So today I will finish the review of OOP in Wolrfam \
Language, but first of all I want to show that all the things I wrote above \
are not just a toy, but are used by me and my friends in our pet projects. It \
is this implementation of changeable objects that I am gradually adding to \
many of my projects and it works great, even though it \
doesn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t have everything I planned. Here is for example the \
code used in the TelegramBot library:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.91292256253096*^9},ExpressionUUID->"42fb923c-2279-4260-b94a-a85b909d5d80"],

